Part 32: How To Split Your BIG Ash Resources for Cleaner Code and Faster Compilation

Ash Framework for Phoenix Developers

Kamaro Lambert
5 min read
Nov 2, 2025

Over the past few years, I have enjoyed working with the Ash framework. The more I work with it, the more my resources grow with hundreds of lines of code, and the slower compilation becomes.

If you havent encountered this problem yet, you will soon, as long as your resources continue to grow.

Today, I want to introduce you to Ash resource fragmentation to show you how to resolve this problem. It makes your code DRY, well organized, and faster to compile.

Before you continue, please take a moment to register for my upcoming book Ash Framework for Phoenix Developers to not miss its release this year and gain content that will supercharge your Phoenix projects with Ash framework.

Ash is built using Spark, an Elixir tool to build premium domain specific language(DSL). Thus, we can use Spark.Dsl.Fragment to split a resource into small and well organised modules.

How It Works

Two things are needed to organize a big resource into smaller modules:

  • Extract resource definition into subsets module A.K.A fragments.
  • Inform the parent

Lets see it in action.

Assume that you have a big resource with definitions such as the following:

# lib/my_app/members/member.ex
defmodule MyApp.Members.Member do
  use Ash.Resource,
    domain: MyApp.Members,
    data_layer: AshPostgres.DataLayer,
    authorizers: [Ash.Policy.Authorizer]

  postgres do
    table "members"
    repo MyApp.Repo
  end

  actions do
   # 7 Actions 
  end

  policies do
   # 10 policies
  end

  attributes do
    # 30 attributes
  end

  relationships do
    # 5 relationships
  end

  calculations do
    # 13 Calcuations 
  end

  graphql do
    # more definitions here.
  end
  identities do
    identity :unique_member_number, [:member_number]
  end
end

If we add rest_api and other configurations, the Member resource will become cluttered, look less elegant, be hard to navigate, and definitely be hard to maintain.

Lets change that by splitting it into small parts (fragments), each with a single responsibility. Attributes will be in their own module, actions will be in their own module, and the same for relationships and the rest of the blocks.

Lets start by moving actions into their own module, like below:

# lib/my_app/members/member/actions.ex
defmodule MyApp.Members.Member.Actions do
  # 1. Indicate that this is a subset of Spark Dsl
  use Spark.Dsl.Fragment,
    # 2. Indicate the type of Spark Dsl this subset belongs to. 
    # Since it is for a resource, we use `Ash.Resource`.
    # If it is for domain, you can use `Ash.Domain`.
    of: Ash.Resource

  # You will define action like you'd normally do
  # in your non-fragmented resources.
  actions do
    default_accept [
      :signature,
      :email,
      :province,
      :district,
      :institution_id,
      :first_name,
      :last_name,
      :date_of_birth,
      :gender,
      :national_id,
      :nationality,
      :telephone,
      :bank_id,
      :bank_account,
      :monthly_fees,
      :employee_id,
      :termination_date,
      :photo
    ]

    defaults [:read, :update, :destroy]

    create :create do
      description "Add a new member to the team"
      change MyApp.Members.Member.Changes.AddMemberNumber
      change MyApp.Members.Member.Changes.AddUserAccount
    end
  end
end

Note how in the Actions module, weve used Spark.Dsl.Fragment and of: Ash.Resource. Those are the magic elements that Ash reads and understand that this is a subset module. The rest of the definitions are the same.

Next, we need to inform Member resource that it has a subset to load from another module, then list the subset modules. To do so we use fragments: [].

Since fragments accepts a list, we can add as many fragments as we want. Go to the parent resource and add fragements like below.

# lib/my_app/members/member.ex
defmodule MyApp.Members.Member do
  use Ash.Resource,
    domain: MyApp.Members,
    data_layer: AshPostgres.DataLayer,
    authorizers: [Ash.Policy.Authorizer],
    # Tell Ash that this resource has a subset defined 
    # in Actions module that must be loaded.
    # Since it is an list, we can add more
    fragments: [MyApp.Members.Member.Actions]

  postgres do
    table "members"
    repo MyApp.Repo
  end

 # Other resource definitions
end

The code will continue to work as expected, but now, it is organised better, easy to maintain, and compiles faster. What weve done with actions can be done with attributes, relationships, policies, and the rest.

Lets try again with attributes this time.

  1. Define attributes in a separate module as fragment, then
  2. Tell Member resource to load that fragment.

Define attributes in a subset fragement.

# lib/my_app/members/member/attributes.ex
defmodule MyApp.Members.Member.Attributes do
  use Spark.Dsl.Fragment, of: Ash.Resource

  attributes do
    uuid_v7_primary_key :id

    attribute :member_number, :string do
      description "Unique adhesion number assigned to the member."
      allow_nil? false
    end

    attribute :province, :string do
      description "The province where the member resides (e.g., Kigali, Bugesera)."
      allow_nil? false
    end

    attribute :district, :string do
      description "The district within the province where the member is located."
      allow_nil? false
    end

    attribute :first_name, :string do
      description "The first name of the member."
      allow_nil? false
    end

    attribute :last_name, :string do
      description "The last name of the member."
      allow_nil? false
    end

    attribute :date_of_birth, :date do
      description "The date of birth of the member."
      allow_nil? false
    end

    attribute :gender, :string do
      description "The gender of the member (male or female)."
      allow_nil? false
    end

    attribute :national_id, :string do
      description "The national identification number of the member."
      allow_nil? false
    end

    attribute :nationality, :string do
      description "The nationality of the member (e.g., Rwandese)."
      allow_nil? false
    end

    attribute :email, :string do
      description "The email address of the member."
      allow_nil? false
      constraints match: ~r/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/
    end

    attribute :telephone, :string do
      description "The telephone number of the member."
      default "No Phone provided"
      allow_nil? true
    end

    attribute :bank_account, :string do
      description "The bank account number of the member."
      default "No account provided"
      allow_nil? true
    end

    attribute :monthly_fees, :decimal do
      description "The monthly fees paid by the member (optional)."
      allow_nil? true
    end

    attribute :employee_id, :string do
      description "The employee ID, defaulting to 'general_not_available' and non-editable."
      allow_nil? true
      default "general_not_available"
    end

    attribute :termination_date, :date do
      description "The date when the member's membership terminates (optional)."
      allow_nil? true
    end

    attribute :photo, :string do
      description "The file path or URL of the member's uploaded photo."
      allow_nil? true
    end

    attribute :signature, :string do
      description "The file path or URL of the member's uploaded signature."
      allow_nil? true
    end

    timestamps()
  end
end

Then, tell Member resource to load it as a fragment. You can do the same for relationships.

# lib/my_app/members/member.ex
defmodule MyApp.Members.Member do
  use Ash.Resource,
    domain: MyApp.Members,
    data_layer: AshPostgres.DataLayer,
    authorizers: [Ash.Policy.Authorizer],
    # Tell Ash that this resource has a subset defined
    # in Actions module that must be loaded.
    # Since it is an list, we can add more
    fragments: [
      MyApp.Members.Member.Actions,
      MyApp.Members.Member.Attributes,
      MyApp.Members.Member.Relationships
    ]

  postgres do
    table "members"
    repo SocialFund.Repo
  end

Also, fragments accept ash extensions as you would normally load them in your resource. For example, if you want to extract graphql definition in their module, you can do it like below:

# lib/my_app/members/member/graphql.ex
defmodule MyApp.Members.Member.Graphql do
  use Spark.Dsl.Fragment,
      of: Ash.Resource,
      # Fragments can load dependant extensions like you'd do it in
      # a normal resource
      extensions: [AshGraphql.Resource]
      
  graphql do
   # Your graph definitions
  end
end

Now that you know how to split your big resource into small, solid, elegant and easy to maintain module, try it and let me know if it reduces compilation time and gives better organised code base.
